.TH RM(1),User Commands,RM(1)

.SH NAME
rm - remove files

.SH SYNOPSIS
rm file ...

.SH DESCRIPTION
rm unlinks each named file.
At least one operand is required.

rm opens each file for reading before unlinking, so a non-existent file is reported rather than silently ignored.

rm does not remove directories;
use rmdir(1) for those.

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
rm: missing operand - no arguments were given.

rm: error removing 'X': No such file - the file did not exist.

rm: error removing 'X': Unknown error - unlink failed for some other reason (permission, directory, etc.).

After reporting an error, rm continues with the remaining operands.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: No operands were missing.
rm exits 0 even if some removals failed.

1: No operand was given.

.SH SEE ALSO
rmdir(1)
